
Problem statement:
The Problem: You are a thief with a knapsack that can hold a maximum weight w . There are
N items in a room. Each item has a weight and a value . You want to maximize the total
value in your bag.

The constraint is "0/1": You can either take the item whole (1) or leave it (O). You cannot break it.

Step 1: Think Recursively (The "Choice" Diagram)
Imagine you are standing at the last item (index n-1 ). You have a bag with some remaining
capacity w . You have exactly two choices for this item:

1. Don't Pick it (Exclude): You decide this item is too heavy or not valuable enough. You skip
it and move to the next item (index n-2 ) with your bag capacity unchanged.

2. Pick it (Include): You put it in your bag. You gain its value , but your bag capacity shrinks
by its weight . You then move to the next item (index n-2 ) with less capacity.

Note: You can only pick the item if its weight is less than or equal to the current bag capacity.

Step 2: The Recursive Line (Recurrence Relation)

Our state needs two variables: the index of the item we are considering, and the current
capacity of the bag.

f(i,w)= max(Don'tPick, Pick)

Where:

. Don'tPick = f(i-1,w)
· Pick = value[i] + f(i - 1, w - weight[¿])

Pattern  identification:
· How to Identify:
· You are given a set of items with attributes (cost, value, weight).

· You have a constraint or a target (max weight, target sum).

. You need to select a subset of these items to maximize/minimize a value or count
ways.

. Typical Questions:
· 0/1 Knapsack: Maximize value within weight limit.

. Subset Sum: Is there a subset of numbers that sums up to K ? (Here, "value" is
ignored, we just care if capacity becomes O).

. Partition Equal Subset Sum: Can you split an array into two subsets with equal
sums?


class Solution {
// dp[index][weight]
int[][] memo;

public int knapsack(int[] weights, int[] values, int capacity, int n) {
// Initialize memoization table
// Rows: items (0 to n), Cols: capacity (0 to capacity)
memo = new int[n][capacity + 1];
for (int[] row : memo) java.util.Arrays.fill(row, -1);

// Start thinking from the last item
return solve(weights, values, n - 1, capacity);

private int solve(int[] weights, int[] values, int index, int currentCap) {
// Base Case: We ran out of items
if (index < 0) {
return 0;

// Base Case: If we are at the very first item (index 0)
if (index == 0) {
// If we have space, we steal it. Otherwise 0.
if (weights[0] <= currentCap) return values[0];
return 0;

// Return if already calculated
if (memo[index] [currentCap] != -1) return memo[index] [currentCap];

// CHOICE 1: DON'T PICK
// Move to index-1, capacity stays same
int notPick = 0 + solve(weights, values, index - 1, currentCap);

// CHOICE 2: PICK
// Move to index-1, capacity reduces by weights[index]
// Add values[index] to our profit
int pick = Integer.MIN_VALUE;
if (weights[index] <= currentCap) {
pick = values[index] + solve(weights, values, index - 1, currentCap - weights[index]);

// Store and return the max of the two choices
return memo[index] [currentCap]=Math.max(pick, notPick);

}
